.SH FILES
.TP
.B .kensa/results.db
Default SQLite transaction log in the current directory. Created on
first
.B kensa check --store
or
.B kensa remediate
invocation. Override with
.B --db PATH .
.TP
.B $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/kensa/
.TQ
.B ~/.config/kensa/
.TQ
.B /etc/kensa/
Config-directory search path for rule-variable defaults
(\fIdefaults.yml\fR), per-host overrides (\fIhosts/<addr>.yml\fR),
per-group overrides (\fIgroups/<name>.yml\fR), and conf.d drop-ins.
The first match in this order wins; override with
.B $KENSA_CONFIG_DIR
or
.B --config-dir DIR .
.TP
.B /usr/share/kensa/rules/
Default rule corpus location for distro packages (post-M7). Today
.B --rules-dir DIR
is required at runtime.
.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B KENSA_CONFIG_DIR
Override the config-directory auto-detect chain. When set, the chain
collapses to this single path.
.TP
.B KENSA_NO_DEPRECATION_WARNINGS
Set to
.B 1
to silence flag-deprecation warnings (e.g.,
.B --format ,
.B --oscal
slated for removal in v0.2). Exact-match on
.B 1
\(em other values do not silence.
.TP
.B KENSA_NO_REPURPOSE_WARNINGS
Set to
.B 1
to silence the
.B kensa coverage
v1.1 repurpose warning. Distinct from KENSA_NO_DEPRECATION_WARNINGS:
operators who silenced flag warnings months ago should still see the
louder semantic-flip signal.
.TP
.B KENSA_TEST_SSH_HOST
.TQ
.B KENSA_TEST_SSH_USER
Used by integration tests in
.B internal/transport/ssh
and
.B cmd/kensa-fuzz .
Not consumed by the operator-facing CLI.
.TP
.B GODEBUG=netdns=go
Recommended at runtime to enforce the pure-Go DNS resolver baked in at
build time
.RB ( -tags=netgo ).
Belt-and-suspenders against the cgo resolver if it sneaks back.
.
.SH EXIT CODES
.TP
.B 0
Success, including
.B --help
and
.B --version .
.TP
.B 1
Runtime error: subcommand started but failed to complete (rule not
found, host unreachable, signature verification failed, partial-
success multi-txn rollback, etc.).
.TP
.B 2
Usage error: invalid invocation (bad flag, unknown subcommand,
missing required arg, mode mux violation). Per GNU/POSIX convention.
.PP
The 1-vs-2 distinction is load-bearing: CI scripts can distinguish
"the command was wrong" from "the command was right but the data
isn't ready" with a single-byte check. See
.B kensa info ,
.B kensa rollback ,
.B kensa diff
help text for the per-command exit-code contract.
.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR ssh (1),
.BR sshpass (1),
.BR sqlite3 (1)
.PP
Project documentation:
.UR https://github.com/Hanalyx/kensa-go
.UE
